    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Lead-Paint Law</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Joseph Strasburg of Rent Stabilization Assn notes dramatic decline in number of children with elevated blood levels of lead, as well as research that children are safer when old lead paint is not disturbed</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''E.P.A. Says Lead-Paint Law May Increase Risks to Children'' (news article, Sept. 29):</p>
        <p>The number of children in the city with elevated blood lead levels has declined dramatically.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''E.P.A. Says Lead-Paint Law May Increase Risks to Children'' (news article, Sept. 29):</p>
        <p>The number of children in the city with elevated blood lead levels has declined dramatically.</p>
        <p>Health Department statistics show a 22 percent drop in lead poisoning cases for the first six months of 2000 -- only 263 new cases reported, compared with 340 in the same period in 1999. The rate of decline is even more striking when compared with new cases reported over the last two full years -- 1,062 cases in 1998 and 896 in 1999.</p>
        <p>Scientific research concludes that the less lead paint is disturbed, the safer children are. Contrary to fears generated by trial lawyers, the existing system of laws and regulations fully protects the city's children.</p>
        <p>JOSEPH STRASBURG  President  Rent Stabilization Association  New York, Oct. 2, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
